The George Brown College in Toronto offers a Blockchain Development program that lasts for three semesters. The curriculum focuses on the design and deployment of decentralized applications using blockchain technology. Students will learn skills such as smart contracts design, full stack development, integration of blockchain architecture, security practices, and more.

The program is delivered in a full-time executive format requiring approximately 20 hours of study each week over a 26-week duration. In the third semester, students have the option to engage in a Co-op placement or work-integrated learning experience.

The technology requirements for the program include a personal computer with a minimum of 8 GB RAM (16 GB recommended), 256 GB SSD Hard Drive (500+ GB is optimal), Quad-core i5/i7 2.4GHz or better, and the ability to run Ubuntu 20.04 (can be on a virtual machine). Students also need a webcam.

Graduates of this program may apply for positions such as blockchain engineer, blockchain developer, blockchain architect, smart contract developer, dApp developer, blockchain solution analyst, or blockchain consultant. Career options include the blockchain industry to support Toronto as a leading blockchain city.

The George Brown College offers a three-semester blockchain solution analyst or consultant program in partnership with ConsensSys and ChainSafe Systems. The curriculum includes the following courses:

Semester 1:
- BCDV 4001: Blockchain Foundations
- BCDV 4010: Smart Contract Development Essentials
- BCDV 4028: Advanced Smart Contract Development
- BCDV 4010: Decentralized Governance Framework
- BCDV 4001, 4021: Front-end Web Development
- BCDV 4030: Blockchain Business Models
- BCDV 4001, 2029, 4030: DeFi Fundamentals
- BCDV 4021: Back-end Web Development
- BCDV 4022: Full Stack Blockchain Integration
- BCDV 4021, 4022: Full Stack Blockchain Integration <-- II

Semester 2:
- BCDV 4019: Advanced Blockchain Topics
- BCDV 4032: Building Scalable Blockchain Apps
- BCDV 4023: Enterprise Blockchain Development
- BCDV 4023: DevOps and Blockchain Administration
- BCDV 4026: Blockchain Platforms
- BCDV 4033: Full Stack Blockchain Integration - II
- BCGV 4027: Capstone Project
- COMP 4064: Career Planning and Portfolio Development

Semester 3:
- TCOP 4007: Co-op Work Placement
- BCDV 4015: Work-Integrated Project

The program learning outcomes include the ability to communicate essential concepts related to blockchain technology and its industry applications, and implement best practices in the field.

The text provides information on how to apply for admission to George Brown College, specifically for domestic and international students. It also mentions the Transfer Guide for course exemptions, contact details for the School of Computer Technology and its Program Coordinator, and campus visit options. Here's the extracted information:

- Students can check the Transfer Guide for credit transfer information.
- International students should visit the International Admissions page for country-specific admission requirements.
- Domestic students should apply through Ontario Colleges.
- International students should apply via George Brown College Online Application System.
- The School of Computer Technology can be contacted at 416-415-5000, ext. 4287 or email: computertechnology@georgebrown.ca. Office hours: Monday – Friday, 9 a.m. – 4 p.m.
- Program Coordinator: George Petrovic, email: Djordje.Petrovic@georgebrown.ca.
- Contact the college via the Contact Centre at 416-415-2000 (TTY 1-877-515-5559) or long distance 1-800-265-2002.
- International recruitment representatives can be contacted through the International Contact Us page for country-specific queries.
- The Blockchain Development program is offered at Casa Loma Campus, 146 Kendal Avenue.
- Information sessions and campus tours are available at George Brown College.
- Related programs: Computer Programming and Analysis (T177), Information Systems Business Analysis (Postgraduate) (T405), Computer Systems Technology (T147).
- Contact details for booking a campus tour or info session and signing up to receive application resources are provided in the text.
